inces: Bavaria, Franconia, and Swabia. The region was the geographical and political dimension within which succeeding bishops, with great tenacity and inventiveness, survived the threat of dominion by their secular neighbors, the counts. The bishops of Eichstätt were able to emerge with a durable territorial structure of their own, which they succeeded in recasting, between 1280 and 1320, into a credible and long-lasting principality. Modern ideas of political progress, Arnold contends, tend to be unfair to medieval institutions that have not left easily recognizable descendants. He argues that it would be more prudent to observe in the territorial fragmentation of Germany not the triumph of chaos but the outcome of a reasonably orderly social and legal process that provided alternative institutions to those of a centralized or national monarchy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aConstitutional history, Medieval. 0aNobilityzGermanyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aRegionalismzGermanyxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEuropean History.  aHistory.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aWorld History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Package Archive 1898-1999z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978151280010440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781512800104423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781512800104/original  a978-3-11-044252-6  University of Pennsylvania Press Package Archive 1898-1999c1898d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK